MOFs composite layer was in-situ prepared on the electrode surface by electrochemically assisted self-assembly method (Scheme 1). Briefly, the GCE was immersed in an electrodeposition solution containing AuNPs and CDs, KNO3 as a support electrolyte, H3BTC as an organic ligand, and Zn(NO3)2 as a Zn2+ source. The electrogeneration of OH− at the GCE surface under −1.3 V lead to the increase in the local pH, the deprotonation of the ligands, and finally self-assembly of MOFs crystal from needle to columnar forms with the increase of electrodeposition time on the electrode [6,15]. Herein, the electrogeneration of OH− plays an important role in self-assembly of MOFs crystal on the GCE surface. As Fig. 1
                         shown, MOFs was needle like forms (Fig. 1A) in the early stage of MOFs crystal growth (t = 200 s), which is consistent with the literature [15]. After AuNPs adding, the obtained AuNPs-MOFs composite was still needle like structures with more quantity and higher density at the same condition of preparation (Fig. 1B). And after CDs adding, the similar phenomena was obtained for ErCDs-MOFs composite, and with a little columnar forms (Fig. 1C). When the existence of AuNPs and CDs, there are more and more columnar forms for AuNPs-ErCDs-MOFs composite (Fig. 1D and E) at the same condition of preparation. This interest SEM results exhibit that AuNPs, ErCDs and AuNP-ErCDs can significantly accelerate electrodeposition of MOFs by promoting the release of electrogeneration of OH−. As shown in Fig. 1(F–K), there are Zn, Au and N elements in the AuNPs-ErCDs-MOFs composite. Zn element should come from MOFs polygon. Au and N elements are considered to be from AuNPs and ErCDs (sodium citrate as carbon source and urea as dopant), respectively, and they are evenly distributed in composite. And the amount of AuNPs and ErCDs in MOFs composite (the mass loading of MOFs composite on the electrode is 0.5 mg) are calculated as 0.1 μg and 11.75 μg according to Au and N atomic percentage, respectively (Table 1
                        ).
